    <li>Sherugar, D., & Budiu, R. (2016). <em>User Experience and Usability in Complex Systems</em>. Nielsen Norman Group.</li>
  </ul>

     <!-- Module 2.1 Blog Post Starts here -->
    <h1>Designing for People: A Focus on Empathy, Perception, and Usability within the Framework of Human-Centered Design Approaches</h1>
    
    <p>In today's fast-evolving digital, the commercial success and popularity of a product cannot be merely measured by its functional utility or beauty alone. Instead, it is now widely determined by the degree to which it addresses and fulfills the specific needs, perceptions, and emotional responses of the individuals who utilize it. The term "designing for people" is more than a slogan — it is the cornerstone of human-centered design (HCD). It finds deep-rootedness in empathy, substantially directed by cognitive science research, and driven by an ongoing iterative feedback process that sharpens and maximizes design decisions over time.</p>

    <h2>Introduction to Human-Centered Design</h2>
    
    <p>Human-centered design is a meticulous and creative process aimed at solving problems in an effective manner, but in such a manner that the users are kept at the very center of each and every one of the design decisions made throughout. It emphasizes the need to develop a deep understanding of what people actually need, how they think and perceive, and what drives their behaviors and actions in various contexts. As outlined by the ISO 9241-210 standard, human-centered design is formally defined as a methodology that ensures interactive systems not only are usable but also accessible, through carefully prioritizing users, tasks they are performing, and contexts where they are located at each and every phase of the design and development process (DIN e.V., 2020).</p>
    
    <div class="highlight">
        <p>Unlike other methods, the IDEO Field Guide to Human-Centered Design provides a far more adaptable and reactive process that is focused on the cultivation of a specific mindset. IDEO places great emphasis on the importance of co-creation, including collaboration with a range of stakeholders, and rapid prototyping that allows for fast iterations and revisions, along with encouraging the adoption of failure as a step towards genuine innovation. IDEO offers that "human-centered design offers problem solvers of any stripe a chance to design with communities… and create innovative new solutions rooted in people's actual needs" (IDEO.org, 2015, p. 9). This perspective emphasizes working directly with individuals and groups of people to ensure that solutions developed are actually in accordance with people's true needs.</p>
    </div>
    
    <p>In spite of the marked differences in tone and structure between IDEO's and the ISO guide, it is imperative to observe that these two useful documents emphasize and reiterate a central insight: for design to be optimally effective, it must reflect and convey an essential and deep understanding of human experience.</p>

    <h2>ISO 9241-210 vs. IDEO's Field Guide: Structure vs. Mindsets</h2>
    
    <p>ISO 9241-210 defines a formal six-step process:</p>
    
    <ol>
        <li>Organize the human-centered design process</li>
        <li>Identify and define the context of use</li>
        <li>Identify user needs</li>
        <li>Develop design solutions</li>
        <li>Evaluate designs</li>
        <li>Iterate as necessary</li>
    </ol>

    <p>This specific approach is especially useful in strongly regulated fields or in projects where high traceability and effective risk management actions are needed (DIN e.V., 2020).</p>
    
    <p>IDEO's Field Guide, in contrast, takes a comprehensive approach as it introduces three distinct nonlinear phases that are critical to the design process: Inspiration, Ideation, and Implementation. Additionally, it promotes a robust set of seven core design mindsets that practitioners need to embrace, viz. Empathy, Optimism, Iteration, Creative Confidence, Making, Embracing Ambiguity, and Learning from Failure (IDEO.org, 2015, pp. 10–14). This particular edition is focused on creating a culture of flexibility and creativity and is thus particularly handy in settings such as social innovation or startup-heavy settings.</p>
    
    <p>In reality, designers tend to borrow from both. ISO brings structure; IDEO provides inspiration.</p>

    <h2>Perception and Visual Hierarchy: Designing for the Mind's Eye Experience</h2>
    
    <p>Designing for perception necessarily involves a deep understanding of the intricate way that individuals process and interpret visual information. It is essential to recognize that our brains are wired to seek order, to appreciate contrast, and to crave simplicity in the information that we take in. This is where the concept of visual hierarchy becomes crucial and plays a key role—it is the purposeful arrangement of several elements to successfully guide users' attention. In doing so, it renders interfaces intuitive and easy to use, rather than confusing and overwhelming.</p>
    
    <p>Consider the example of a flight booking application. If the "Book Now" button is reduced in size, has poor contrast with other page elements, or located at the bottom of a page full of other content and distractions, the chances are extremely high that the user may completely overlook it. But if this same exact button is positioned centrally in a visible spot, has a high degree of contrast so that it can be easily spotted, and has ample space surrounding it, it will effectively attract the user's attention, thereby inviting them to take action.</p>
    
    <p>This general principle is essentially related to Fitts's Law, which is an established principle in human-computer interaction, and this law provides that the time required to finish the acquisition of a target or an object is directly related to its size and to its distance from the user. According to this law, bigger buttons that are placed within the reach of easy access significantly decrease the effort required by users while, simultaneously, enhancing overall efficiency in their use (Fitts, 1954). This is precisely the reason why key actions and main features on mobile applications are typically placed at the bottom part of the screen, where it is easily within the reach of the thumb.</p>

    <h2>The Importance of Concentration and the Value of Simplicity</h2>
    
    <p>Designing for care also means reducing cognitive overload. According to Hick's Law, the more choices a user has, the longer it will take to decide. A 3–5 item navigation menu that is clearly labeled is preferable to a 15 item one. Simplification doesn't remove complexity; it organizes it.</p>
    
    <p>Miller's Law strongly substantiates this idea. According to the findings of Miller's research, human beings are able to hold approximately 7 ± 2 independent items in working memory at any given point (Miller, 1956). It is precisely this inherent cognitive constraint that some interface elements, such as dropdown menus, the convention of progressive disclosure, and the tendency to chunk information into reasonable segments—such as in common online forms or instructional onboarding tutorials—are not merely fleeting design trends or fashions. Rather, they are essential cognitive imperatives that are addressing our innate capacities for information storage and processing.</p>
    
    <div class="highlight">
        <p>Both statutes highlight the value of minimalism in design. Less really is more—when less enables the user to think less.</p>
    </div>

    <h2>Empathy and Familiarity: The Core of Human-Centered Design</h2>
    
    <p>Jakob's Law offers perhaps the most comforting observation: people prefer systems that act in a manner consistent with systems they are already familiar with. This is the reason new sites follow the structure of older sites. Innovation is needed, but excessive deviation from set norms creates friction. This particular law has a tight relationship with the concept of empathy, which is the main cornerstone for the methodologies employed both by ISO and IDEO. IDEO also clarifies the meaning of empathy as "the ability to put oneself in other people's shoes, to understand their lives, and begin to solve problems from their points of view" (IDEO.org, 2015, p. 22). Without a deep sense of empathy, it is extremely hard, if not impossible at all, to truly comprehend how users interact with a product in real-life situations or to ascertain the precise challenges and issues they encounter in doing so.</p>
    
    <p>When embarking on the mission of designing a health-tracking application that is tailored to elderly users, a designer with a strong sense of empathy will be sharply aware that certain design choices, such as the inclusion of small font sizes, rapid animations, or complicated multi-step login processes, are significant usability barriers. Accordingly, this designer will prioritize the selection of readable fonts, the design of straightforward user flows, and the presence of adequate feedback mechanisms, not only for good aesthetics, but fundamentally because these design choices add to the overall good of the user experience and make the application feel genuinely usable and accessible to the target audience they are trying to help.</p>

    <h2>Iteration and Evaluation: Embracing the Valuable Feedback and Learning from Failure to the Fullest</h2>
    
    <p>One other important principle that is highlighted in both frameworks is that of iterative design. The ISO standard requires products to be created via a process of continuous assessment that directly engages actual users throughout. It is critical to realize that feedback should not simply be treated as the last step in development; instead, it serves as an essential part of a continuous cycle that informs and refines the design.</p>
    
    <p>IDEO also states that "failure is an incredibly powerful tool for learning" (IDEO.org, 2015, p. 21). Prototypes, even crude paper ones, can reveal issues early. Prototyping allows for testing, which provides designers the opportunity to course correct prior to investing heavily in development. As an example, a startup launching a chatbot can utilize a method whereby they simulate the speech given by a human operator; this method is called the Wizard of Oz prototype. Using this approach, the startup has an easy way to test conversational flow and quantify user expectations without even writing one line of code.</p>

    <h2>Final Reflections: Creating Solutions to Complicated Issues with Genuine Empathy and Understanding</h2>
    
    <p>Designing for human beings not only demands intellectual rigor, but also high degrees of emotional intelligence. It is important that we put clear frameworks to our processes as talked about in ISO 9241-210, so that we will be able to ensure consistency and effectiveness while remaining flexible and positive in the process, which is a core value held by IDEO. In our design thinking, we must not only think of cognitive factors of perception and memory, but we must pay proper attention to the key factors of trust and dignity in what we do.</p>
    
    <div class="highlight">
        <p>As designers, we hold the pivotal position of shaping the interactions that significantly impact individuals' daily lives. These include the way we conveniently order food, the way we effectively receive essential healthcare services, and even the way we learn through various learning processes. Such a huge responsibility requires more than technical skill; it also requires that we exercise profound reflection, are culturally aware, and have unflinching commitment to actively hear others' needs and experiences. Designing for people requires us to ask better questions, to look at the world through other people's eyes, and to never assume we've "got it right" on the first try.</p>
    </div>

    <h2>References</h2>
    <p class="reference">DIN e.V. (2020). Usability and user experience design: The ISO 9241-210 standard. In R. Albers et al. (Eds.), Usability and User Experience Design (pp. 81–88). Rheinwerk Publishing.</p>
    <p class="reference">IDEO.org. (2015). The field guide to human-centered design. https://www.designkit.org/resources/1.html</p>
    <p class="reference">Fitts, P. M. (1954). The information capacity of the human motor system in controlling the amplitude of movement. Journal of Experimental Psychology, 47(6), 381–391. https://doi.org/10.1037/h0055392</p>
    <p class="reference">Miller, G. A. (1956). The magical number seven, plus or minus two: Some limits on our capacity for processing information. Psychological Review, 63(2), 81–97. https://doi.org/10.1037/h0043158</p>

<div class="container"> 
<header> 
<h1>What Makes Digital Systems Usable: An Examination of the Role of Memory, Habits, and Attentive Cognitive Design</h1> 
</header> 
<main> 
<section>
<p>Usability in digital systems is so much more than merely the visual appearance and feel of elements and interfaces. It implies that the system is not just easy but also intuitive, enabling users to readily grasp concepts and utilize the features without unnecessary complexity. Good and well-considered design matters in assisting individuals in getting their job done efficiently, while eliminating the feeling of confusion or stress along the way. Such a seamless experience happens when the system adopts the natural cognitive behaviors and memory processes that humans naturally engage in. Based on the fact that our brains inherently possess limitations with regard to information processing, it is incumbent upon good design to bear such limitations in mind, ensuring that it augments and assists users rather than working against them (Johnson, 2020).</p>
</section>

<section>
<h2>Memory, Mental Models, and Interaction</h2>
<p>Most of the time, individuals tend not to recall all the information they encounter in their lifetimes. In fact, our working memory capacity is rather limited and can only retain a finite amount of information at a given moment. This hinders people to aid the process of recognition of options rather than the process of recalling the options. For instance, it is mostly much simpler and easier to click on an option in the menu compared to trying to recall a particular command. This is precisely the reason why websites and applications have to put options and features in front of the users instead of behind them.</p>
<p>Another key and core concept to talk about is what is known as the "mental model." This particular term is used to define how individuals think and understand how a specific system operates or functions. When the system is functioning in a manner that is contrary to the expectations of the users, or what they are searching for, it creates confusion and ambiguity for the user. For instance, consider a case where an individual is accustomed to a "back" button that consistently brings them back to the previous page they were viewing. But if this same button were to bring them to the main page all of a sudden, they would definitely get confused and would be lost (Johnson, 2020). The concept of a mental model is key because it makes individuals gain a sense of control when interacting with the system. They are confident in the system when it behaves in the way they expect.</p>
<p>I used to have a printer program that made me choose the paper size and printer each time. I expected that it would recall them. Since it did not, I kept making mistakes. This shows how incompatibility of mental models and lack of memory support make systems harder to use.</p>

<figure>
<img src="https://tse4.mm.bing.net/th?id=OIP.yquMLAD0WnaPgPIEMfPC_gHaHr&pid=Api" alt="Diagram showing UX psychology principles including memory limitations and mental models">
<figcaption class="image-caption">Key psychological principles that influence digital usability</figcaption>
</figure>
</section>

<section>
<h2>Consistency and Feedback: Foundations of Usability</h2>
<p>One of the most critical and basic usability guidelines that is most emphasized is the law of consistency. This particular principle is talking about the fact that it is essential to have the same look and feel throughout the entire system one is using. When elements such as buttons, icons, and labels all visually resemble one another and behave in the identical manner, individuals are able to learn and adapt much more quickly. For instance, when the "trash" icon always means one is deleting something, users can instantly understand what will occur when they decide to click on it (Krug, 2014).</p>
<p>Feedback is extremely crucial for any user interface. When the user performs some action on the system by clicking a button or doing something else, it is necessary for the system to respond. This helps them understand that their action has been executed successfully. Feedback can be given in various forms, such as the audible tone of sound, a visual change in color, or even a brief flash of text. For instance, after a user submits a form, showing a message of simply "Thank you" conveys the message to the user that the form has been submitted successfully. But without the feedback, the users may remain confused and can even attempt to try the same operation again in a hope to find the desired result.</p>
<p>This type of event has the ability to lead to all manner of errors, or even lead individuals to consider abandoning the use of the system altogether (Budiu, 2023).</p>

<figure>
<img src="https://tse2.mm.bing.net/th?id=OIP.gR5lzjDM2K5KIN3p7ePGfAHaFJ&cb=iwp1&pid=Api" alt="Infographic showing core usability principles including consistency and feedback">
<figcaption class="image-caption">Essential usability principles every designer should implement</figcaption>
</figure>
</section>

<section>
<h2>Cognitive Load and the Various Design Traps</h2>
<p>Cognitive load is the amount of mental effort that is needed for a person to be able to use a system effectively. As the cognitive demands go higher, it becomes much harder for the user to use the system in an efficient way. A good system is engineered in such a way that the cognitive load remains low. This means that users are not subjected to the necessity of having to think too much or keep too many bits of information in their heads at the same time (Johnson, 2020). To put this argument into perspective, if a certain system subjects users to five different kinds of menus to navigate through, it is possible that users will feel tired or frustrated within a short period of time because of too many options.</p>
<p>Poor design is a frequent complaint. I once used a shopping site where the discount field was at the top of the page, but the promo code input was at the bottom. I kept missing it. This frustrated me because I couldn't finalize my order effortlessly. Little glitches like this get users to believe that the system is broken when it isn't.</p>
<p>This specific issue has close relevance to the principle that goes by the name Tesler's Law. In accordance with Tesler, he advocated for the fact that any system does inherently contain some amount of complexity which is inherent. Note that it is not complexity which can be totally eradicated; it is something which can be moved or transferred, that's all. A good and well-constructed system is able to hide the more difficult and more complicated aspects from the user so that they experience it smoother. Designers have an important choice in front of them: whether they wish to take care of the complexity themselves or wish to pass the burden of it on to the end user. Ultimately, an optimally usable system assigns the responsibility and weight of handling that complexity on the designer's part, instead of leaving it to the user who is utilizing the system (Babich, 2023).</p>
<p>As explained in Chapter 9 of the Laws of UX, Tesler's Law is an important reminder to designers, emphasizing the requirement to curb the amount of cognitive load imposed on the user. This can be achieved quite effectively by taking proper care of complicated complexities in the background, thereby facilitating a better user experience. When this law is implemented successfully, users are able to experience an uninterrupted and smooth interaction, often without even being aware that the system is more than capable of performing a series of complex logical functions on their behalf (Babich, 2023).</p>

<figure>
<img src="https://tse2.mm.bing.net/th/id/OIP.mF7QOLyTbgR1s7-XjdxcxgHaGi?cb=iwc1&pid=Api" alt="Examples of consistent UI design patterns across applications">
<figcaption class="image-caption">Consistent UI patterns reduce cognitive load across digital products</figcaption>
</figure>
</section>

<section>
<h2>Takeaways from Designing with the Mind in Mind</h2>
<p>Jeff Johnson's book Designing with the Mind in Mind has plenty of great suggestions for ways to simplify digital systems to make them more usable. Two important points from Chapters 6–9 are:</p>
<ol>
<li>"People can't keep much in working memory." That is, a system must not ask users to remember steps or details from page to page. Keep everything in sight. Make actions clear (Johnson, 2020).</li>
<li>"People learn better by doing." This principle calls on designers to let users experiment. Explain through example. Keep it simple to reverse. In this way, users will be able to learn while in a state of comfort (Johnson, 2020).</li>
</ol>

<h3>Practical Uses in Everyday Life and Personal Insight</h3>
<p>Everyday digital tools demonstrate how usability is done—or isn't. Apple's iPhone, for instance, is commended for its uncluttered, consistent design. The buttons are where you always expect them to be, and gestures such as swipe and tap are reliable. This minimizes learning over and over (Norman, 2013).</p>
<p>On the other hand, government websites often feel confusing. Pages are long, options are hidden, and there's little feedback after submitting a form. This makes users feel nervous or lost. A form I filled out once didn't show if my data was saved. I had to re-enter it several times. That's an example of high cognitive load and poor usability.</p>
<p>Another example is the clear difference between large e-commerce behemoth Amazon and smaller e-commerce websites that exist. Amazon effectively guides the customer through their shopping process with concise instructions to perform, progress indicators that inform consumers of their status, and helpful suggestions that can enhance consumers' shopping process. Smaller sites often overlook or omit these essential functions, which can result in a checkout process that is more challenging and confusing for consumers to navigate.</p>
</section>

<section>
<h2>Conclusion</h2>
<p>In conclusion, making a digital system usable and user-friendly needs an understanding of how the human mind works. One should keep in mind that humans do not have a perfect or ideal memory. Instead, they prefer familiar things that they recognize, contrary to products or features that they must remember from their memory. Also, users expect to get feedback every time they take any type of action within the system. It is also vital to accept the fact that people may get stressed out when subjected to too much cognitive load or when too much thinking is needed to use the system.</p>
<p>Good systems play a crucial role in allowing individuals to be successful in what they are doing. They accomplish this by accurately mapping onto users' mental models, maintaining consistent layouts throughout the experience, offering beneficial feedback, and minimizing the overall effort required to utilize the system. Designers must keep Tesler's Law in mind, which states that all systems possess a certain degree of complexity inherent in them. The follow-up question that arises from this law is: who bears the brunt of this complexity—designers or users?</p>
<p>By adhering to fundamental cognitive principles and being mindful of how we design, we can create systems that not only function well but also feel supportive and effortless to use. This quality of being smooth and compliant is precisely what enables digital systems to be usable in the first place.</p>
</section>

